full_text: Supervisor Sue Smith sees an activity in her desktop activities view to review and approve a new payment. The activity has a priority of urgent. She clicks on the subject to open the activity. This activity tells her everything she needs to know about the payment that requires her review and approval. Sue enters a justification for her approval of the payment. After entering the approval rationale, she clicks, Approve, to let processing of the payment continue. When Sue approves the check, the approval activity is marked completed. Since she had enough authority to approve the full amount of the payment, no additional approval activities appear in the work plan, and processing of the check continues. Note that when Sue approved the payment, she clicks Approve, to let processing of the payment continue. She accessed the payment, she accessed the Henderson claim itself, and is now viewing its work plan. She navigates to the claim financial summary to see the current status of the check. The financial summary shows a total paid amount of $4,200 for auto body claim cost for the vehicle exposure. This matches the amount of the checks you just approved. She navigates to the financial checks view. The check is now in awaiting submission status. This means that Claim Center is attempting to send the check information to a check writing system. Once the information has been sent, the status in Claim Center will update to submitted. This ends the supervisor review and approved payments demonstration. segments.text: Supervisor Sue Smith sees an activity in her desktop activities view to review and approve a new payment. The activity has a priority of urgent. She clicks on the subject to open the activity. This activity tells her everything she needs to know about the payment that requires her review and approval. Sue enters a justification for her approval of the payment.

After entering the approval rationale, she clicks, Approve, to let processing of the payment continue. When Sue approves the check, the approval activity is marked completed. Since she had enough authority to approve the full amount of the payment, no additional approval activities appear in the work plan, and processing of the check continues. Note that when Sue approved the payment, she clicks Approve, to let processing of the payment continue.
She accessed the payment, she accessed the Henderson claim itself, and is now viewing its work plan. She navigates to the claim financial summary to see the current status of the check.

The financial summary shows a total paid amount of $4,200 for auto body claim cost for the vehicle exposure. This matches the amount of the checks you just approved. She navigates to the financial checks view.

The check is now in awaiting submission status. This means that Claim Center is attempting to send the check information to a check writing system. Once the information has been sent, the status in Claim Center will update to submitted. This ends the supervisor review and approved payments demonstration.
